Without a name I remained unreal in regained consciousness. PoorVivian, poor Vadim Vadimovich, was but a figment of somebody's--not even myown--imagination. One dire detail: in rapid Russian speech longishname-and-patronymic combinations undergo familiar slurrings: thus "PavelPavlovich," Paul, son of Paul, when casually interpellated is made to soundlike "Pahlpahlych" and the hardly